    <h3 style="color: white; margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 1rem;">Educational Deep Dive: Common Naming Conventions in Programming</h3>
    <p style="color: rgba(255,255,255,0.8); line-height: 1.6; margin-bottom: 1rem;">
        If you've ever looked at computer code, you've probably noticed that programmers don't use spaces in their variable names. Instead, they use specific "naming conventions" to keep their code readable and compatible with compilers.
    </p>
    <p style="color: rgba(255,255,255,0.8); line-height: 1.6; margin-bottom: 1rem;">
        <strong>camelCase</strong> (like `myVariableName`) is the standard in JavaScript and Java, where every word after the first starts with a capital letter. <strong>snake_case</strong> (like `my_variable_name`) is common in Python and SQL, using underscores instead of spaces. There is also <strong>PascalCase</strong>, which is like camelCase but starts with a capital letter (used for classes). Using the Webtigo converter lets you quickly switch between these styles without retyping!
    </p>

